In France, voting has traditionally been a low technology experience: voters isolate themselves in a cabin and put a preprinted paper sheet indicating the candidate of their choice in an envelope.
After the officials verify the identity of the voter, the voter casts an envelope in the ballot box and signs the list of voter names.
The French electoral law codifies the procedures rather strictly.
Since 1988, voting boxes of ballots have been transparent so that voters and observers can see that no envelopes are present at the start of the vote and that no envelopes are added except those of the ballots are counted and duly authorised.
